'''Stuttgart 21''' (for 21st century) is a major railway and urban development project in [[Stuttgart]], Germany, that is replacing the surface railway lines with tunnels. It is a part of the [[Stuttgart–Augsburg new and upgraded railway]] and the [[Main Line for Europe]] (Paris—[[Vienna]]) within the framework of the [[Trans-European Networks]]. Its core is a renewed underground [[Stuttgart Hauptbahnhof]], among some {{convert|57|km|mi|abbr=off}} of new railways, including some {{convert|30|km|mi|abbr=off}} of tunnels and {{convert|25|km|mi|abbr=off}} of high-speed lines. The project was highly controversial up to 2010, and still is since, due to destruction of old structures, large area construction works, high costs, and ongoing duration. 
The still operational central [[Train_station#Terminus|terminus station]], with 16 surface platforms shortened and with impeded access due to the large construction pit, is going to be replaced by an underground [[Through station|through-station]] with only 8 platforms.

The project was officially announced in April 1994. Construction work began on 2 February 2010.<ref name=rt7march2013>{{cite web|url=http://www.railway-technology.com/news/newsdeutsche-bahn-backs-stuttgart-21-project-despite-cost-increase|title=Deutsche Bahn backs Stuttgart 21 project despite cost increase|date=6 March 2013|access-date=7 March 2013|archive-date=25 January 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125073428/https://www.railway-technology.com/news/newsdeutsche-bahn-backs-stuttgart-21-project-despite-cost-increase|url-status=dead}}</ref> In March 2013, total costs were officially estimated at €6.5&nbsp;billion, the previous estimate being €4.5&nbsp;billion in 2009.<ref name=rt7march2013/> In March 2022, Deutsche Bahn estimated the total cost at €9.15&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.zeit.de/wirtschaft/2022-03/stuttgart-21-kosten-neun-milliarden|title=Kosten für Stuttgart 21 steigen auf über neun Milliarden Euro|trans-title=Costs for Stuttgart 21 rise to over nine billion euros |date=March 18, 2022|publisher=Die Zeit |language=de}}</ref> Heated debate ensued on a broad range of issues, including the relative costs and benefits, geological and environmental concerns, as well as performance issues.

In 2019, operations had been expected to start in December 2025,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bahnprojekt-stuttgart-ulm.de/projekt/ueberblick/projektstatus/|title=Projektstatus|date=October 28, 2019|publisher=Bahnprojekt Stuttgart-Ulm|language=de|archive-date=March 8, 2021|access-date=October 28, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210308004738/https://www.bahnprojekt-stuttgart-ulm.de/projekt/ueberblick/projektstatus/|url-status=dead}}</ref> delayed from the initial estimation of 2019 (made in 2010). In 2024, the opening date for main elements of the project was delayed again, to December 2026.<ref name="yahoo finance 2024 delayed to 2026">{{cite news |last1=Atack |first1=Patrick Rhys |title=Stuttgart 21 confirms yet another setback |url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/stuttgart-21-confirms-yet-another-135549654.html?guccounter=1&guce_referrer=aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZ29vZ2xlLmNvbS8&guce_referrer_sig=AQAAAEUIZyAhz0-rlX3HkB2cj-fX-UYDdPlr8TZK3QIsVcGZ8LlCEe5TLV9tKvOw9Ci2wyMGLf-PWBZ5u3TkkIZkWWV9cuVNZuRdpuB3gRbF2rWUiL0s470K0i8BQ0EGAgaGBR44I5hliUMh0_hKfolDvigpqjLnv2q09azl9bvWv_fo |access-date=14 June 2024 |work=Yahoo! Finance |date=13 June 2024}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.msn.com/de-de/nachrichten/welt/stuttgart-21-vollst%C3%A4ndige-er%C3%B6ffnung-verschoben-neuer-zeitplan-bekannt/ar-AA1ICEvZ?|title=Stuttgart-21-Start soll teilweise auf 2027 verschoben werden|trans-title=start partially delayed till july 27|date=2025-07-18|accessdate=2025-07-19|work=msn}}</ref> In 2025, the planned opening date of December 2026 was canceled, officially due to technical issues with the new signaling system.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hallam|first1= Mark|title='Stuttgart 21' high-speed rail opening delayed once more|url=https://www.dw.com/en/stuttgart-21-high-speed-rail-opening-delayed-once-more/a-74805775| access-date=20 November 2025|work=Deutsche Welle|date=19 November 2025}}</ref>

==Concept==
[[File:Gleisplan 3.svg|thumb|Principal track layout of the future Stuttgart main railway station]]
[[File:Flughafenschleife Stuttgart 21.png|thumb|Stuttgart airport and fair grounds. Both the existing and a new station are to be connected with the Stuttgart–Wendlingen high-speed line (red).]]
The concept attempts to combine plans for high-speed links from Stuttgart to other cities with the improvement of local infrastructure and replacement of the current terminal station. The current 16-track station is to be replaced by an underground 8-track through station which is currently under construction.

The new tracks are planned to cross below ground at right angles to the northern end of the existing building. Parts of the historic [[Paul Bonatz|Bonatzbau]] building, the platforms and approach tracks are to be demolished, and the land sold for urban development.

The plans include new surface and underground lines connecting the station in Stuttgart's enclosed central valley with existing lines. The [[Stuttgart–Wendlingen high-speed railway|Stuttgart–Wendlingen high-speed line]] running through a new tunnel, the Filder Tunnel, would connect the replacement Hauptbahnhof with a new Filder station (''Filderbahnhof''), serving the [[Stuttgart Airport|Airport]], the [[Stuttgart Trade Fair|''Messe'' (trade fair)]] and the [[Filderstadt]] district. The line would then connect to the new [[Wendlingen-Ulm high-speed railway line|Wendlingen-Ulm high-speed line]], which was opened in late 2022. The carriage sidings would be moved to the area of [[Stuttgart-Untertürkheim station|Untertürkheim station]] to clear land for redevelopment.

On 2 April 2009, the Premier of [[Baden-Württemberg]], [[Günther Oettinger]], signed the finance agreement with the [[Federal Ministry of Transport, Building and Urban Affairs (Germany)|German Minister of Transport]], [[Wolfgang Tiefensee]] and [[Deutsche Bahn]] board member Stefan Garber.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.spiegel.de/reise/aktuell/0,1518,617037,00.html |website=
spiegel.de|language=de |title=Minister besiegeln Milliardenprojekt der Bahn |trans-title=Ministers sealrailway project worth several billions |date=2009-04-02 |access-date=2023-09-21}}</ref><ref name=TR2009June>{{Cite journal|journal=[[Today's Railways Europe]]| title=Stuttgart 21 and Stuttgart-Ulm NBS funding agreed |page=9|date=June 2009}}</ref>

On 23 November 2009, it was announced that construction would commence in February 2010, on condition that the overall costs do not exceed €4.5&nbsp;billion.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.stuttgarter-zeitung.de/stz/page/2287550_0_4248_-drexler-nennt-termin-februar-2010-baubeginn-fuer-stuttgart-21.html |trans-title=Drexler: Excavators will start work in February |title=Drexler: Bagger rücken im Februar an |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091126024601/http://www.stuttgarter-zeitung.de/stz/page/2287550_0_4248_-drexler-nennt-termin-februar-2010-baubeginn-fuer-stuttgart-21.html |archive-date=2009-11-26 |publisher=Stuttgarter Zeitung |date=23 November 2009 |language=de}}</ref>

DB subsidiary [[DB ProjektBau]] has planned the project on behalf of [[DB Netze]] and [[DB Station & Service]] and is its promoter for the development approval process.
[[File:S21-Baustelle-pjt.jpg|thumb|Construction site for the new underground station (April 2022)]]

==Debate and opposition==
The Stuttgart 21 project has been a controversial issue among politicians and local people ever since the idea of a through station for long-distance trains – running under the existing station – was first proposed in the mid-1980s.

[[File:MittlererSchlossgartenKundgebung 2010-10-01.jpg|thumb|More than 50,000 people demonstrated against Stuttgart 21 on 1 October 2010.]]
[[File:Stuttgart 21 Ende.svg|Symbol of the protest against Stuttgart 21|thumb]]
[[File:StuttgartHauptbahnhofNordfluegel 2010-08-26.jpg|thumb|Demolition works and protest demonstration at the north wing of Stuttgart Hauptbahnhof, 26 August 2010]]

Since late 2006, there have been negotiations between [[Deutsche Bahn|DB]], the Federal Government, the Baden-Württemberg Government and the city of Stuttgart over the sharing of the costs of the project. On 28 June 2007, a high-level conference was held and adjourned between DB chairman [[Hartmut Mehdorn]], Baden-Württemberg Minister of Finance Gerhard Stratthaus and Stuttgart mayor [[Wolfgang Schuster]]. At the meeting, agreement could not be reached over the allocation of construction cost risks.<ref name="stuttgart-2007-06-29">{{Cite news | title =Entscheidung über Baukostenrisiken vertagt |trans-title=Decision on construction cost risks postponed | language =de | publisher =Stuttgart Nachrichten | date =29 June 2007 | url =http://www.stuttgarter-nachrichten.de/stn/page/detail.php/1457698?_suchtag=2007-06-29 | access-date =2007-07-20 | url-status =dead | archive-url =https://archive.today/20070712080204/http://www.stuttgarter-nachrichten.de/stn/page/detail.php/1457698?_suchtag=2007-06-29 | archive-date =12 July 2007 }}</ref>

