Shortly after the funding agreement was announced, the political opponents of [[Wolfgang Schuster]] were quick to condemn the Stuttgart mayor for backtracking on a promise made during the 2004 mayoral elections – namely that he would allow the population of Stuttgart to decide the fate of Stuttgart 21 if the additional costs of the project amounted to more than €200&nbsp;million. On hearing the promise at the time, [[Alliance '90/The Greens]] candidate [[Boris Palmer]] withdrew his candidacy for the second round vote, recommending that his supporters should back Schuster instead.<ref name="stuttgart-2007-07-21">{{Cite news
| title =Stuttgart 21 – Gegner erinnern an Wahlzusage
| trans-title = Stuttgart 21 – Opponents remind of election promise 
| language =de
| publisher =SWR Radio news
| date =21 July 2007
| url =http://www.swr.de/nachrichten/bw/-/id=1622/nid=1622/did=2387316/pyrcro/index.html
| accessdate =2007-07-21
| archive-date =2020-04-14
| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20200414140751/http://www.swr.de/nachrichten/bw/-/id=1622/nid=1622/did=2387316/pyrcro/index.html
| url-status =dead
}}</ref>

In October 2007, a [[petition]] and public demonstrations were started, sponsored by private individuals with the backing of [[Alliance '90/The Greens]] and a variety of citizens' and environmental organisations. The aim was to collect 20,000 signatures and thus force politicians to take the issue to a local referendum. The petition gained 67,000 signatures{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} but political wrangling began over whether the issue could be decided by a local referendum in the first place. Legal experts claimed that, as the project was not being financed solely from Stuttgart coffers, it was not for the city of Stuttgart to make the final decision.<ref name="stuttgart-2007-11-17">{{cite news
| title =Stuttgart 21 – Juristischer Streit gewinnt an Schärfe
| trans-title =Stuttgart 21 – Legal dispute getting more heated 
| language =de
| newspaper =Stuttgarter Zeitung
| date =17 November 2007
| url =http://www.stuttgarter-zeitung.de/stz/page/detail.php/1568790
| accessdate =2007-11-19
| archive-date =2019-12-11
| archive-url =https://web.archive.org/web/20191211150344/https://www.stuttgarter-zeitung.de/
| url-status =dead
}}</ref>

On 11 October 2008, about 4,000 citizens of Stuttgart demonstrated against the demolition of the Hauptbahnhof's north wing.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}} Since the fall of 2009, there have been weekly demonstrations on Monday evenings. On 1 October 2010, the biggest protest so far took place with an estimated 100,000 people taking part in the demonstration against the project.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/world/2010/1005/1224280400563.html|title=Protest threatens to derail Merkel's election plans|newspaper=The Irish Times|date=2010-10-05|archive-date=2012-10-22|access-date=2010-10-05|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121022090729/http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/world/2010/1005/1224280400563.html|url-status=dead}}</ref>

[[File:StuttgartHauptbahnhofNordfluegelBauzaun.jpg|thumb|Protest manifestations on the fence during demolition works]]
The protests are organized by, among others, a [[grassroots]] initiative, ''Leben in Stuttgart'' (Life in Stuttgart), the local branch of [[Alliance 90/The Greens|The Greens]] and the environmental organisation [[Bund für Umwelt und Naturschutz Deutschland]]. They are suggesting a renovation of the current railway station, including creation of some new railways, but respecting the [[cultural heritage]] of the Hauptbahnhof terminus and the [[natural heritage]] of the adjacent ''Schlossgarten'' (Palace Park). The park (see [[Old Castle (Stuttgart)]] and [[New Castle (Stuttgart)]]) by [[Nikolaus Friedrich von Thouret]], is part of a cherished green space that connects the inner city with the banks of the [[Neckar]] river. During the estimated construction time of at least 10 years, the project would cut off connections to other park areas of the city, known collectively as the ''Green U'' due to their U-shaped form. In November 2009, members of the [[International Council on Monuments and Sites]] stated that the Hauptbahnhof was a building of exceptional quality, whose integrity should be maintained.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://stuttgarter-zeitung.de/stz/page/2290433_0_7998_-denkmalschuetzer-appell-bonatzbau-soll-weltkulturerbe-werden.html|title=Bonatzbau soll Weltkulturerbe werden | trans-title =Bonatzbau should become a world cultural heritage site |newspaper=Stuttgarter Zeitung|date=2009-11-25|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091127073958/http://www.stuttgarter-zeitung.de/stz/page/2290433_0_7998_-denkmalschuetzer-appell-bonatzbau-soll-weltkulturerbe-werden.html|archive-date=2009-11-27}}</ref>

=== "Black Thursday" ===
Since 2009 numerous protests against the disputed project had taken place. On 30 September 2010, hundreds of demonstrators were injured when the police used [[water cannon]], [[pepper spray]] and [[Baton (law enforcement)|batons]] against protestors.<ref name="stuttgart-2010-09-30">{{cite news | title =Germany Shocked by 'Disproportionate' Police Action in Stuttgart
| work =Spiegel Online
| date =1 October 2010
| url =http://www.spiegel.de/international/germany/0,1518,720735,00.html
| accessdate = 2010-10-01}}</ref> One citizen, [[Dietrich Wagner]], permanently lost his eyesight.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/stuttgart-21-fast-erblindeter-aktivist-will-entschuldigung-von-mappus-a-736829.html | title =Stuttgart 21 – fast erblindeter Aktivist will Entschuldigung von Mappus| trans-title =Stuttgart 21 – almost blind activist wants apology from Mappus |newspaper=Der Spiegel |date= December 28, 2010 |language=de}}</ref> The event was widely referred to as "Black Thursday" in the media. The police chief of Stuttgart, who was present at the scene, was subsequently charged with, and convicted of [[Battery_(crime)|battery]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.stuttgarter-zeitung.de/inhalt.schwarzer-donnerstag-ex-polizeichef-stumpf-akzeptiert-geldstrafe.4e89f361-d7f0-4d6d-8f41-c6284c0abf59.html | title =Schwarzer Donnerstag. Ex-Polizeichef Stumpf akzeptiert Geldstrafe | trans-title =Black Thursday.  Former police chief Stumpf accepts fine |newspaper=Stuttgarter Zeitung |date= March 18, 2015 |language=de}}</ref>

The following day, more than 50,000 people took part in the biggest demonstration against the project so far.

Prior to that escalation, [[Frei Otto]], one of the architects responsible for the project, cited a 2003 report for calling for a halt to the project, saying the ground in the area is too unstable for large scale underground works.<ref name="stuttgart-2010-10-01-2">{{Cite news
| title = Stuttgart 21-Architekt fordert den sofortigen Baustopp
| trans-title =Stuttgart 21 architect calls for an immediate stop to construction 
| language = de
| publisher = Stern
| date = 26 August 2010
| url = http://www.stern.de/wirtschaft/immobilien/gefahr-fuer-leib-und-leben-stuttgart-21-architekt-fordert-den-sofortigen-baustopp-1596547.html
| accessdate = 2010-10-02}}</ref> Some critics suggest the cost of the project might rise to €18.7&nbsp;billion.<ref name="stuttgart-2010-01-02">{{cite news
| title =Experten geben Politik Schuld am Demo-Debakel
| trans-title =Experts blame politics for the protest debacle
| language = de
| work = Spiegel Online
| date = 2 October 2010
| url =http://www.spiegel.de/politik/deutschland/0,1518,720882,00.html
| accessdate = 2010-10-02}}</ref>

